      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my physics final and im kinda stuck on quantum entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? i dont need the heavy math right now just a conceptual explanation",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two particles become linked so that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance between them. It's different from classical correlation because in classical physics, correlations arise from shared history or hidden variables, whereas in quantum mechanics, the particles don't have definite states until measured. This non-local connection is often described as \"spooky action at a distance,\" a phrase coined by Einstein, who was skeptical of it.\n\nTo visualize this, imagine two coins that are entangled. In a classical scenario, if you flip two coins that were prepared together, they might both land heads because they were set up that way. But in quantum entanglement, the coins don't have a determined state until you look at them. If you measure one and it shows heads, the other will instantly show tails, even if it's on the other side of the galaxy. This instantaneous correlation defies our classical intuition of how objects should behave.\n\nThe key difference lies in the nature of the information transfer. Classical correlations can be explained by pre-existing information, but quantum entanglement involves a superposition of states that only collapses upon measurement. This means the particles are not just correlated;",
      "source": "target",
