    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so even though it's called \"spooky action at a distance,\" there's no actual signal or physical force traveling between the particles, right? it just happens. it feels a bit like magic or something, how does science actually explain that weirdness without just calling it spooky?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You've hit on the exact reason why Einstein was so bothered by it! He felt it violated his principle of \"local realism,\" which basically says that nothing can travel faster than light and that objects only have definite properties when they interact with something.\n\nScience explains this \"weirdness\" by saying that the particles aren't just magically talking to each other; rather, they share a single, unified quantum state from the moment they are created. Think of it less like two separate entities communicating and more like a single entity split in two. If you have a single coin that is magically duplicated into two halves, and you look at one half, you instantly know what the other half is doing because they are fundamentally the same object, just separated.\n\nThe \"magic\" is actually just the weirdness of superposition. Until you measure them, neither particle has a definite state (like heads or tails); they exist in a blur of both possibilities simultaneously. The moment you measure one, you force the entire system to \"choose\" a state, and because they are one system, the choice is immediate for both.\n\nTo put it in a **goblin** way: Imagine two goblins, one in your room and one in the next room",
      "source": "target",
